==English==

===Etymology===
Coined between 1500 and 1510 from {{etyl|la}} {{term|alacritas|alacritās|lang=la}},<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/alacrity "Alacrity" in Dictionary.com]</ref> from {{term|alacer||brisk|lang=la}} + {{term|-itas||-ity|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|/əˈlæk.ɹɪ.ti/|/əˈlæk.ɹə.ti/}}, {{SAMPA|/@"l{k.rI.ti/}}
*: {{audio|en-us-alacrity.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|alacrities}}

# [[eagerness|Eagerness]]; [[liveliness]]; [[enthusiasm]].
#* '''1837''', [[w:Charles Dickens|Charles Dickens]], ''The Pickwick Papers'', ch. 12:
#*: "I'll get into the clothes this minute, if they're here," said Sam, with great '''alacrity'''.
#* '''1922''', [[w:Edith Wharton|Edith Wharton]], ''The Glimpses of the Moon'', ch. 24:
#*: This evening, however, he was struck by the beaming '''alacrity''' of the aide-de-camp's greeting.
# [[promptness|Promptness]]; [[speed]].
#* '''1849''', [[w:Henry David Thoreau|Henry David Thoreau]], "On the Duty of Civil Disobedience":
#*: Yet this government never of itself furthered any enterprise, but by the '''alacrity''' with which it got out of its way.
#* '''1902''', [[w:Joseph Conrad|Joseph Conrad]], ''Heart of Darkness'', Part 1:
#*: He had a uniform jacket with one button off, and seeing a white man on the path, hoisted his weapon to his shoulder with '''alacrity'''.

